      <title>High levels of cellphone radiation linked to cancer in male rats</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANResearchers have found evidence of links between tumors in male rats and exposure to radio frequency radiation.A final report released on Thursday by the U.S. National Toxicology Program details an experiment in which about 3,000 rats and mice were exposed to whole body radio frequency radiation nine hours a day for up to two years. Rats began exposure to the radiation in the womb while mice started at 5-6 weeks old. The radiation used in the experiment was similar to those emitted by 2G and 3G mobile phones. The rodents lived in specially designed chambers with isolated rooms where a transmitting antenna subjected the rats to RFR fields with frequencies of 900 and 1900 megahertz. The study found evidence that radiation exposure was associated with the emergence of tumors in the hearts, brains, and adrenal glands of male rats. However, cancers found in female rats and male and female mice weren't conclusively linked to radio frequency radiation exposure.The research cost $30 million and was ongoing for a decade. The NTP's goal was to gather information on the effects of mobile phone radiation on rats in response to the increasing universality of cellphone use among humans. However, NTP scientists and the U.S. Food and Drug Administration stated that the results of the research do not directly affect humans since the rodents were exposed to extreme levels of cellphone radiation, which surpass the current safety limits on mobile phone radiation. The results also do not apply to Wi-Fi signals or phones that use 4G or 5G technologies, these use different methods of signal modulation that the NTP did not study in their research.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Introduction and duration of research2. Details of rats experimented on3. Details of experiment: how it was carried out.4. Results of experiment: cancer on male ratsVOICEOVER (in English): "A U.S. National Toxicology Program experiment exposed about 3,000 rats and mice to whole body radio frequency radiation nine hours a day for up to two years."  "Rats began exposure to the radiation in the womb while mice started at five to six weeks old.""Rodents lived in specially designed chambers, where a transmitting antenna subjected them to RFR fields with frequencies of 900 and 1900 megahertz.""The study found evidence that exposure to radiation is associated with tumor development in the hearts, brains and adrenal glands of male rats."SOURCES: National Toxicology Program, New York Timeshttps://ntp.niehs.nih.gov/results/areas/cellphones/index.htmlhttps://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/01/health/cellphone-radiation-cancer.html***]]></description>
