      <title>Ancient Egyptian tomb found to contain cat mummies, statues</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANEgypt's Ministry of Antiquities has announced that dozens of mummified cats and wooden cat statues have been discovered in the ancient city of Memphis, Egypt.Along with the mummified cats and wooden cat statues, a painted wooden cobra and a crocodile sarcophagi were also found.Gilded statues of a lion, a cow and a falcon were also discovered, along with wooden snakes and crocodiles.Objects such as amulets, canopic jars and papyri baskets were also discovered in the tomb.The artifacts are regarded to be around 6000 years old.Ancient Egyptians were often buried with their mummified animals and statues as a way to bring pets with them to the afterlife.The animals were also buried as food offerings for not just the deceased, but as offerings to the gods as well.The ministry is hoping the discoveries will attract more tourists to visit Egypt's heritage sites.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Mummified cat and wooden cat statue 2. Painted wooden cobra and a crocodile sarcophagi3. Amulets, canopic jars and papyri baskets4. Mummies buried with mummified catsVOICEOVER (in English): "Egypt's Ministry of Antiquities has announced that dozens of mummified cats and wooden cat statues have been discovered in the ancient city of Memphis, Egypt.""Along with the mummified cats and wooden cat statues, a painted wooden cobra and a crocodile sarcophagi were also found.""Objects such as amulets, canopic jars and papyri baskets were also discovered in the tomb.""Ancient Egyptians were often buried with their mummified animals and statues as a way to bring pets with them to the afterlife."SOURCES: NPR, Live Science, The Washington Post, The Independent, The Guardian, https://www.npr.org/2018/11/11/666