      <title>Six rescued from skyscraper elevator accident in Chicago</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANSix people were rescued from an elevator after it plummeted more than 80 floors down a Chicago skyscraper.The Chicago Tribune reports that six people stepped into an express elevator on the 95th floor of Chicago's John Hancock Center around midnight on Friday. Two cables holding the elevator broke soon after.The people inside said they felt the elevator moving fast and saw a dust-like material enter the carriage. The elevator fell 84 floors before stopping at the 11th floor.Firefighters had to use a gooseneck camera to determine the elevator's exact location, before then breaking through a brick wall to open the doors and rescue the people trapped inside.The rescue took nearly three hours. A Chicago Fire Department Spokesman told the Chicago Tribune that none of those trapped suffered serious injuries. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Six passengers in elevator; cables holding elevator snaps2. Elevator plummets from 95th to 11th floor3. Camera used to determine exact location in blind elevator shaft4. Firefighters break through a brick wall to rescue passengersVOICEOVER (in English): "Six people stepped into an express elevator on the 95th floor of Chicago's John Hancock Center around midnight on Friday. "Two cables holding the elevator broke soon after.""People inside said they felt the elevator moving fast and saw a material that looked like dust begin seeping in. "The elevator fell 84 floors before suddenly stopping near the 11th floor.""Because of the building's blind-shaft layout, there were no openings between floors." "Firefighters had to use a gooseneck camera to determine the elevator's exact location.""They then broke through a brick wall to open the doors and rescue the people trapped inside."SOURCES: Chicago Tribune, CBS, ABChttps://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-met-hancock-building-elevator-rescue-20181116-story.htmlhttps://www.cbsnews.com/news/chicago-elevator-plunges-rescue-875-north-michigan-avenue-building-formerly-the-john-hancock-center/https://abcnews.go.com/US/elevator-drops-84-floors-cables-snap-chicagos-famed/story?id=59299860***]]></description>
