      <title>China to assign social credit scores to citizens by 2020</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANChina is planning to launch a social credit system that will assign  "personal trustworthiness points" as a means of monitoring citizens and businesses.Reuters reports that trustworthy individuals will reportedly be provided with more access to society while individuals who are blacklisted will be severely restricted.Credit history, contract obligation fulfillment, character traits, behavior, preferences, and interpersonal relationships will all be considered in calculating a credit score.Data gathered by the system could impact an individual's access to public services and employment. It may also affect a citizen's ability to start a business. People with high trustworthy scores could be given easier market access.Participation is currently not mandatory. Once it becomes required, however, people with low scores could be punished with slower internet speeds, denied travel, and access to certain restaurants, night clubs, golf courses.Beijing plans to implement its social credit system by 2020.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Subway riders each with a social credit score2. Individuals deemed trustworthy by the government are on the safe side while those who aren't are blacklisted3. Citizens are given an individual score based on several factors4. Ways citizens could be impacted by their social credit score5. How businesses could be impacted by their social credit score6. Citizens with low scores could have access to certain things restricted7. China wrapped with a Chinese flag and a calendar iconVOICEOVER (in English): "According to Reuters, China is planning to launch a social credit system in which the government will assign "personal trustworthiness points" to monitor its citizens and businesses.""Trustworthy individuals will reportedly be provided with more access to society while individuals who are blacklisted will be severely restricted.""Everything from credit history, contract obligation fulfillment, character traits, behavior, preferences and interpersonal relationships will all be taken into account to calculate a credit score.""Data gathered on the system could also impact an individual's right to use public service and employment.""The data could also affect one's ability to start a business. People with high trustworthy scores could be given easier market access."  "Participation is currently not mandatory, however once it is, people with low scores could be also punished with slower internet speeds, denied access to certain restaurants, night clubs, golf courses or not being allowed to travel.""Beijing plans to implement its social credit system by 2020."SOURCES: Reuters, StraitsTimes, The Telegraph, The Independent, The Wired, Xinhuahttps://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-society-points/beijing-pioneering-citizens-points-system-critics-brand-orwellian-idUSKCN1NP0FT?utm_source=fark&utm_medium=website&utm_content=link&ICID=ref_farkhttps://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/beijing-pioneering-social-credit-systemhttps://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2018/11/20/beijing-assign-personal-trustworthiness-points-citizens-2021/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/china-social-credit-system-flight-booking-blacklisted-beijing-points-a8646316.htmlhttps://www.wired.co.uk/article/chinese-government-social-credit-score-privacy-invasionhttp://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-11/21/c_137622527.htm***]]></description>
